[8] Shores Nen Hithoel<br>
[9] <a href="javascript:card_browser(242)">Summit of Amon Hen</a>  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> (This is my submission to Decipher&#39;s Designer Challenge II)<br>
<br>
This deck is called &quot;Gandalf&#39;s Go-Cart&quot; for good reason. It uses the Cart and similar mechanics to really speed up the deck. It also attempts to make innovative use of pipeweed, the Moria swarms, and synergy between the free peoples&#39; side and the shadow side. All the cards and tactics are designed to work together for maximum effectiveness. The overall strategy is twilight denial and minion swarming. The two sides work together to accomplish this: the shadow side is a strong Moria orc swarm, with emphasis on card throughput and recursion. The free peoples&#39; side uses pipeweed and Gandalf&#39;s Cart to further increase card drawing, and extreme twilight denial to protect Frodo and clog the opponents hand with useless shadow cards.<br>
<br>
Some of the elements that make this deck unique are:<br>
- It only needs to add 5 or 6 twilight to the pool EVER<br>
- It can generate as little as X - 2 twilight per site (X = shadow number). With Sting, it removes 2-4 of that against the one deck type that can get by on that little (Moria swarm)<br>
- Once Gandalf&#39;s Cart is in play, most free peoples&#39; cards can be played or carted for more draws<br>
- Even with little twilight, the shadow side can play all its cards per turn<br>
- Therefore, the deck can draw about 6 cards per turn<br>
- Redundant cards ensure draws of what&#39;s needed, yet the Cart and They Are Coming can get rid of duplicates quickly<br>
<br>
And most of all:<br>
- It uses an innovative approach to free-peoples/shadow synergy. The free peoples sacrifice staying power for extreme twilight denial. They only move one site per turn, but in doing so prevent the opponent from playing their shadow side well. This disrupts their throughput, preventing them from drawing the cards (Power According To His Stature and Sleep, Caradhras) that can wreck the strong Moria swarm. Best of all, both sides have tremendous throughput, and this deck makes use of drawing cards quickly to overwhelm the opponent.<br>
<br>
<br>
Here&#39;s an overview of the game timeline the deck hopes for (and since it is a control-based deck, it has a good chance of succeeding). You start by bidding high. I mean really high. Like 6 or 7 high. This is because you really want to go first: you get to fetch Sam at the Green Dragon, get to hurt any Prancing Pony-dependent decks, and you get to draw end-of-turn cards before the opponent. If you know an opponent bids low or doesn&#39;t use the Pony, you can bid lower. But with Sam, you can remove three burdens right away, and Aragorn, his pipe, and Stout and Sturdy can heal Sam to remove more.<br>
<br>
In the early game, what the free peoples want is Gandalf&#39;s Go-Cart. Once it&#39;s out, you can dump all possessions for free (although you might actually play the pipeweed, since you get the comes-into-play effect, and enemy minions would still be roaming so you have some leeway with twilight). For fun, put Gandalf&#39;s Go-Cart inside itself. Play No Stranger and Talent For Not Being Seen quickly; you can get rid of duplicates of them through Longbottom Leaf. You&#39;ll want your pipes out pretty quick, but there&#39;s a balance: if the twilight denial really hurts an opponent, you may not need the pipes ASAP. Do try to get The Gaffer&#39;s and Aragorn&#39;s Pipes out though; removing 2-3 twilight and healing 2-3 times per turn will keep Frodo alive and the opponent stumped. If facing Moria, make sure to get Sting! Nasssty goblinsss...<br>
<br>
The early cards that shadow hopes for are They Are Coming and Goblin Swarms. If you can spot Gandalf, you&#39;ll have to be careful of Sleep, Caradhras, but with Sting, you can see it coming. An important note is not to hold on to cards, even the main conditions. Throughput it this deck&#39;s V-8 engine. So discard any duplicates, toss a Goblin Scimitar or two, and play minions just to do so. Remember what Magic: The Gathering teaches us: Goblins are cheap cannon fodder. :) Use Goblin recursion to fuel the main assault when it comes.<br>
<br>
Throughout the game, this deck only moves one site per turn. The fellowship may have the stealth to reach site 9 alive, but that&#39;s not its goal. C&#39;mon, Aragorn and Frodo have read the script; they know what happens around site 9. They may be on a &quot;fool&#39;s errand&quot; but they&#39;re not stupid! They&#39;re going to take their sweet time at nice old Rivendell. :) It just so happens that this strategy denies the opponent enough twilight to get shadow cards out of their hand!<br>
<br>
Moving slowly like this is important: the deck is not designed to handle defending against many minions. And by aiming to not only minimize twilight but actually not leave ANY for the opponent, the deck should really load your opponent&#39;s hand with dead cards, thus making it that much easier for the swarms of Moria to prevail.<br>
<br>
The shadow side shouldn&#39;t need much explanation to those who have seen the goblins at work. Runners and Scouts are twilight-generating first plays, Wallcrawlers and Scavengers are shock troops, and you can toss in Chieftains and Patrol Groups as the big guns. The Commanders are great support troops, and can use left-over twilight. Goblin Scimitars are the best card-drawing engines in the game, and they even generate twilight with Armories. Give them to big guys to overwhelm or little guys to even out your troops for fighting Frodo. And of course, use They Are Coming and Swarms to reuse those goblins!<br>
<br>
<br>
That&#39;s basically it for strategy. The free peoples disrupt the opponent and fill your hand with goblins, that try to assault the fellowship at sites 5 and 8/9. Here are comments on site choices:<br>
<br>
[1] Green Dragon Inn: Deny the Prancing Pony, fetch Sam<br>
[2] Midgewater Marshes: Won&#39;t see play if you go first, but get their Frodo to exert, and low shadow for hiding<br>
[3] Rivendell Terrace: Hurts the least<br>
[4] Moria Stairway: Underground, damage +1 helps goblins, other choice of Mithril Mine is unnecessary with Scavengers<br>
[5] The Bridge of Khazad-dûm: Underground, 6 shadow<br>
[6] Dimrill Dale: Goblins are cheaper here<br>
[7] Anduin Wilderland: No archery = goblins survive :)<br>
[8] Shores Nen Hithoel: 9 shadow, good for goblins<br>
[9] Summit of Amon Hen: Draw cards for the last battle<br>
<br>
<br>
Well, that&#39;s it. Thank you for your endurance if you&#39;ve read all this! I hope someone can have as much fun playing this deck as I had designing and preparing it. And if it does well in the Designer&#39;s challenge, well, I&#39;ll say that I never knew Gandalf&#39;s Go-Cart could get that far! :)<br>
<br>
Xanthix </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=20708"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=20708" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
